@startuml CGI Approach
title 1. CGI Approach — 10 Requests = 10 JVM Processes

skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam BoxPadding 10

actor "Client 1" as C1
actor "Client 2" as C2
actor "Client 3" as C3

box "Web Server" #LightBlue
    participant "Apache/Nginx" as Apache
end box

box "OS — new process per request" #LightCoral
    participant "Process 1\n(JVM boot ~500ms)" as P1
    participant "Process 2\n(JVM boot ~500ms)" as P2
    participant "Process 3\n(JVM boot ~500ms)" as P3
end box

C1 -> Apache: GET /api/todos
Apache -> P1: spawn process\njava -cp myapp.jar Main
activate P1
P1 -> P1: JVM startup
P1 -> P1: run code
P1 --> Apache: raw HTTP response
Apache --> C1: HTTP Response
deactivate P1
P1 -> P1: process killed ✗

C2 -> Apache: GET /api/todos
Apache -> P2: spawn process\njava -cp myapp.jar Main
activate P2
P2 -> P2: JVM startup
P2 -> P2: run code
P2 --> Apache: raw HTTP response
Apache --> C2: HTTP Response
deactivate P2
P2 -> P2: process killed ✗

C3 -> Apache: GET /api/todos
Apache -> P3: spawn process\njava -cp myapp.jar Main
activate P3
P3 -> P3: JVM startup
P3 -> P3: run code
P3 --> Apache: raw HTTP response
Apache --> C3: HTTP Response
deactivate P3
P3 -> P3: process killed ✗

note over P1, P3
  Each request = new JVM process
  Heavy memory usage
  ~500ms startup cost per request
end note
@enduml

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

@startuml Raw Java Socket Approach
title 2. Raw Java Socket — Manual HTTP Parsing

skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam BoxPadding 10

actor "Client" as C

box "Java Application" #LightGreen
    participant "ServerSocket\n:8080" as SS
    participant "Socket\n(per client)" as S
    participant "Your Code\n(manual parsing)" as Code
end box

C -> SS: TCP Connection on port 8080
SS -> S: accept()
S --> C: connection established

C -> S: raw HTTP text\n"GET /api/todos HTTP/1.1\nHost: localhost\n..."
S -> Code: getInputStream()
Code -> Code: readLine()\n→ parse method (GET)\n→ parse path (/api/todos)\n→ parse headers\n→ parse body

Code -> Code: run business logic

Code -> S: getOutputStream()\nwrite raw HTTP text:\n"HTTP/1.1 200 OK\r\n"\n"Content-Type: application/json\r\n"\n"\r\n"\n"[{\"id\":1}]"

S --> C: raw HTTP response

note over Code
  Developer must manually:
  - Parse HTTP method, path, headers, body
  - Write HTTP status line
  - Write response headers
  - Handle connection lifecycle
  - Implement HTTP spec correctly
end note
@enduml

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

@startuml Servlet API Approach
title 3. Servlet API — 10 Requests = 10 Threads in ONE JVM

skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam BoxPadding 10

actor "Client 1" as C1
actor "Client 2" as C2
actor "Client 3" as C3

box "One JVM Process (started once)" #LightBlue
    participant "Tomcat\n(web server)" as Tomcat

    box "Thread Pool" #LightYellow
        participant "Thread 1" as T1
        participant "Thread 2" as T2
        participant "Thread 3" as T3
    end box

    participant "servlet-api\nHttpServletRequest\nHttpServletResponse" as SAPI
    participant "TodoServlet\ndoGet()\ndoPost()" as Servlet
end box

Tomcat -> Tomcat: JVM starts once\nwhen Tomcat starts

C1 -> Tomcat: GET /api/todos
Tomcat -> T1: assign thread
T1 -> SAPI: wrap into HttpServletRequest
SAPI -> Servlet: doGet(req, resp)
Servlet --> T1: write JSON response
T1 --> C1: HTTP Response

C2 -> Tomcat: POST /api/todos
Tomcat -> T2: assign thread
T2 -> SAPI: wrap into HttpServletRequest
SAPI -> Servlet: doPost(req, resp)
Servlet --> T2: write JSON response
T2 --> C2: HTTP Response

C3 -> Tomcat: DELETE /api/todos/1
Tomcat -> T3: assign thread
T3 -> SAPI: wrap into HttpServletRequest
SAPI -> Servlet: doDelete(req, resp)
Servlet --> T3: write JSON response
T3 --> C3: HTTP Response

note over T1, T3
  One JVM — started once
  Threads are lightweight (~1ms)
  servlet-api handles all HTTP parsing
  You only write business logic
end note
@enduml